shared_text:
City of Duquesne Police Department
May 22 at 3:22 PM ·

The City of Duquesne Police Department is sad to announce the passing of former Police Chief Richard “Lefty” Adams. Chief Adams served as the Chief from 1994 until his retirement in 2016. Chief Adams had over 50 years of service with the department serving in various roles including K-9 and Detective. Our condolences to the Adams’ family in these difficult times. Funeral arrangements will be released when they become available.
text:
City of Duquesne Police Department
May 22 at 3:22 PM ·

The City of Duquesne Police Department is sad to announce the passing of former Police Chief Richard “Lefty” Adams. Chief Adams served as the Chief from 1994 until his retirement in 2016. Chief Adams had over 50 years of service with the department serving in various roles including K-9 and Detective. Our condolences to the Adams’ family in these difficult times. Funeral arrangements will be released when they become available.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians –

We have collaborated with the Grable Foundation and the Center for Universal Education at the Brookings Institution to learn more about parents’ beliefs about their children’s education.

Please follow this link to complete this survey by May 25th, which takes approximately 15-20 minutes to complete: https://surveyhero.com/c/CUEBrookings

Your participation will help not only us but also educators across western Pennsylvania and beyond, so that we better engage with, and support you, as parents and guardians.

By completing this survey, you will also be entered into a lottery to win a $100 Visa gift card from Brookings.

Thank you,

Sue Moyer, Superintendent

NEW! DCSD Food Delivery Program Duquesne City School District will be delivering school lunches to its regular bus stops starting Wednesday, April 1. The food drop up schedule will be:

Mifflin & Kennedy Ave. - 11:00 - 11:20 am
Crawford & Wool St. - 11:25 - 11:45 am
Crawford & 5th St. - 11:50 - 12:10 pm
Commonwealthand & Overland Av. 12:20 - 12:40 pm

post_text:
Dear Duquesne Community,

The new school year has begun and we are pleased to report that enrollment is up at Duquesne Elementary. More students are attending our school and riding our buses than in previous years. As a result, this change has caused some delays in bus service on the first few days of school. We apologize if either you or your child have been affected. Please know that we are working as quickly as possible with our transportation provider, PA Coach, to correct these issues. We will continue to keep the community informed as more bus routes and stops are added.

Thank you for your patience and flexibility, and thank you for choosing to bring your kids home to Duquesne Elementary School.

Sincerely,

Eric Harper, Principal
Duquesne Elementary School

Sue Moyer, Superintendent
Duquesne City School District

post_text: Students and staff members from Duquesne City School District had the opportunity to meet Governor Wolf and Lt. Governor Fetterman at the Allegheny Intermediate Unit as Governor Wolf announced that The Pittsburgh Penguins Foundation will receive over $400,000 from the PASmart grants. This grant will help support the Lending Library at the AIU which provides professional development for staff and technologies for students to use in the classroom. post_text: Student Services was created to foster the whole child. The department works very hard in its mission to remove barriers to learning and to create opportunities in which students are given experiences that foster academic, social, and emotional growth. We also bring in programs, guest speakers, organized field trips and positive behavior support programming. We fully utilize our various experiences to support all staff, students, and parents within our district. The department works diligently to create a culture that is safe and caring not only in school but out in the community as well. Our focus is to engage our parents, empower our youth, improve the overall behavior(s) of our students by teaching them positive values that will create a peaceful environment free of conflict.

post_text:
The McKinney-Vento Homeless Assistance Act can help provide school stability for your child if you do not have a permanent home and are:

- Staying with friends because you lost housing.

- Living in a shelter, including transitional programs.

- Staying in motels because you cannot get your own home.

- Living on the streets, in a car, van, tent or other nonpermanent structure.

If any of the above apply to you or someone you know that attends The Duquesne Elementary School, please contact:



Mr. Dedris Davis

Community Engagement Coordinator

300 Kennedy Avenue

Duquesne, PA 15110

Email: davisd@dukesk12.org

Phone: 412.466.9600 ext. 3049

post_text: Students in the Extended Day Program created ornaments for a Christmas tree inspired by the Spring Musical, The Lion King Kids. Students created their ornaments from items such as brown paper bags, tissue paper, construction paper, and styrofoam cups. The tree will be on display at the Jacob Woll Pavilion at Renzihausen Park in McKeesport from December 7th thru 11th 12:00 Noon - 9:00 pm. Admission for Adults and Seniors $2, Children 12 & under are free with one canned good for the needy. Please come out and enjoy a wonderful holiday display put on by our students and other local groups.

post_text:
Peace officer Memorial appreciation dinner was held last night hosted by the junior constables and their families. Over 15 different officers representing departments were:

1. Pennsylvania state Constables 5

2. Duquesne Police department 2

3. Rankin police department 2

4. Pittsburgh Protection 2

5. Rhino Security 3

6. U.S Army 1

7. other 1

30 family members were also in attendance to honor the officers while building a healthy relationship with law enforcement.

post_text:
Duquesne Families,

Please share this link to everyone who can vote. Our school is competing against schools that are much larger and we need to show them what Duquesne pride is all about. Please vote for Ms. Recker's class and pass on the word! Thanks
shared_text:
Pittsburgh Penguins Foundation added 5 new photos to the album: Playoff Classroom Decorating Contest — with Shane McGrath and 3 others.
April 17, 2017 at 10:46 AM ·

Iceburgh is looking to go to the #1 school in Allegheny County and we need your help!

Before the Stanley Cup Playoffs got underway, we asked schools in Allegheny County to show us their Penguins pride! We asked them to decorate their classrooms with whatever they wanted to show us how they are cheering on our Pens.

These are the 5 finalists chosen by the Foundation to compete for a party with Iceburgh!

To vote, first make sure you like the Pittsburgh Penguins Foundation page, then like the original photo in this album! The classroom with the most votes by April 20, 2017 at 12:00 PM EST wins!

Good luck to these schools and get to voting!
